,"1105":"1105","1115":"1115","1135":"1135","1113":"1113","1189":"1189","1199":"1199","about 1115":"about 1115","Aft 1174":"after 1174","about 1189":"about 1189","about 1135":"about 1135","Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Gnosall, Staffordshire, England":"Gnosall, Staffordshire, England","Knightley, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Knightley, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Northwich, Cheshire, England":"Northwich, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Knightley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Knightley (Staffs)."],"variants":[{"name":"Knightly","meanings":["English (Middlesex and Cambridgeshire): variant of <b>Knightley</b>, a habitational name from Knightley in Gnosall (Staffordshire). The placename derives from Old English <i>cniht</i> ‘knight, young man, retainer’ (genitive plural <i>cnihta</i>) + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. This is the usual spelling of the name in Ireland, where it has been establishes since the 17th century."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret de Knightley was born about 1115, in Knightley, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Nicholas Maucovenant de Knightley, was 12 and her mother, Mrs Nicholas Maucovenant de Knightley, was 7. She had at least 1 son with Hugh de Vernon. She died in 1190, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 76."},"et":{"about 1115–1190":"umbes 1115–1190","1115–1190":"1115–1190","1129–1199":"1129–1199","1113–1174":"1113–1174","1135–1190":"1135–1190","1105–1190":"1105–1190","1110–1189":"1110–1189","1190":"1190","about 1190":"umbes 1190","1110":"1110","1174":"1174","1129":"1129","1105":"1105","1115":"1115","1135":"1135","1113":"1113","1189":"1189","1199":"1199","about 1115":"umbes 1115","Aft 1174":"pärast 1174","about 1189":"umbes 1189","about 1135":"umbes 1135","Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Gnosall, Staffordshire, England":"Gnosall, Staffordshire, England","Knightley, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Knightley, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Northwich, Cheshire, England":"Northwich, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1115–1190":"noin 1115–1190","1115–1190":"1115–1190","1129–1199":"1129–1199","1113–1174":"1113–1174","1135–1190":"1135–1190","1105–1190":"1105–1190","1110–1189":"1110–1189","1190":"1190","about 1190":"noin 1190","1110":"1110","1174":"1174","1129":"1129","1105":"1105","1115":"1115","1135":"1135","1113":"1113","1189":"1189","1199":"1199","about 1115":"noin 1115","Aft 1174":"1174 jälkeen","about 1189":"noin 1189","about 1135":"noin 1135","Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Staffordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdi